<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Disappointed at Lack of Arab Unity on Disney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) Saturday implicitly expressed its disappointment at the lack
of Arab unity on a controversial exhibition to be staged by the
U.S. Disney Co..
</P>
<P>
Disney Co. did not make enough concessions because it had
received reassurance that the threats of an Arab boycott of its
products need not be taken seriously, said UAE Minister of
Information and Culture Sheikh Abdullah bin Zayed Al Nahyan.
</P>
<P>
The minister was commenting on a meeting of Arab foreign
ministers in New York on Friday, which resulted in shelving, if
not discarding, the issue of Arab boycott against the American
entertainment giant.
</P>
<P>
The ministers accepted Disney's written assurances that the
upcoming millennium exhibition, due to open on October 1 in
Florida, U.S.A., would not identify Jerusalem as the capital of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has been at the forefront of calling for an Arab
boycott against Disney. The campaign was launched last month after
news emerged that the Israeli pavilion at the exhibition would
portray Jerusalem as the Jewish state's capital.
</P>
<P>
Arab and Islamic countries insist that East Jerusalem should
be the capital of a future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Disney would have made more concessions if some Arab
personalities had not informed it of no need to bother about calls
by the Arab world for punitive measures against it, said Sheikh
Abdullah without naming the personalities.
</P>
<P>
These reassurances made by some Arab individuals made Disney
feel that there was a lack of unity in the Arab position and it
was necessary only to offer limited concessions, he said.
</P>
<P>
He hinted that Disney could have offered to change fully an
Israeli film for the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister praised the efforts made by some Arab and
Muslim countries and the Arab League to dissuade Disney from
accepting the Israeli pavilion as originally proposed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Disney offered to ensure that any reference in the
Israeli pavilion to Jerusalem being the capital of Israel will be
removed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Disney also assured Arabs that the entertainment firm will
not take a position on the question of Jerusalem, and any views
expressed are solely those of exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
He attributed this positive step to the concerted campaign
undertaken by a number of official and non-official Arab bodies to
emphasize the Arab character of Jerusalem, as recognized and
highlighted in international resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed an announcement by Arab League Secretary General
Ahmed Abdel-Meguid after the Arab foreign ministers meeting that
it was considering a proposal to set up a Palestinian pavilion.
</P>
<P>
He urged the league to take all necessary measures to ensure
that such a pavilion is built to highlight the Arab and Islamic
character of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"No one can give up on, or tamper with, the question of the
future of Jerusalem. This campaign has shown clearly that Arabs
and Muslims will never accept any distortion of the character of
Jerusalem, even if such a distortion is simply a matter of an
exhibition," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
