<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Gets Remarkable Revenues From Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has cashed in 5.5 billion
Egyptian pounds (1.62 billion U.S. dollars) out of the 7.5 billion
pounds (2.21 billion dollars) of the gross value of the public
companies privatized, a minister said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Public Business Sector Atef Ebeid told the
country's Middle East News Agency that the remaining proceeds of
the privatized enterprises will be collected in the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
Ebeid's ministry is in charge of the privatization program.
</P>
<P>
Egypt kicked off in 1995 the privatization process of 314
state-owned firms. So far, more than one third of the firms have
been totally or partially sold to foreign investors or domestic
private sectors.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the early retirement scheme for workers in the
privatized companies, Ebeid said that about 2.4 billion pounds
(705.88 million dollars) have been paid to 120,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out the possibility of privatizing the state-owned
pharmaceutical companies in a bid to secure reasonable medicine
prices.
</P>
<P>
But he said the government might tender part of the companies'
shares for public subscription, without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, 44 more companies will be put on sale
at 6.6 billion pounds (1.94 billion dollars), including four
cement companies, the Eastern Tobacco Company and a paint company,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Ebeid said that the government will sell five chain stores to
financial concerns instead of selling their shares in the stock
exchange.
</P>
<P>
The privatization program has significantly improved Egypt's
economy and helped the country maintain one of the best economic
performances in the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
