<HEADLINE> Arabs, INTERPOL Work to Combat Crimes, Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Arab Interior Ministers
Council has signed a memo of understanding on cooperation with the
International Criminal Police Organization (INTERPOL), a statement
said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The memo was signed during a visit last Wednesday by Secretary
General of the Arab Interior Ministers Council Ahmed bin Mohamed
al Salem to the headquarters of INTERPOL.
</P>
<P>
The memo is aimed at boosting cooperation between the two sides
in fighting against crime in all forms, the statement by the
council said.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Al Salem held a string of meetings with
senior officials of INTERPOL on various ways of strengthening
cooperation and coordination between the two sides in all fields,
especially in combating terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries have attached importance to cooperation in
combating terrorism and organized crimes. The 22 members of the
Arab League signed an anti-terrorism pact in April 1998 which
took effect in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
