<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti, Jordanian Bourses to be Tied Together </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwait Stock
Exchange (KSE) and its Jordanian counterpart are poised to
consolidate future cooperation by linking themselves together
early next year, a KSE official said here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The link agreement between the Kuwaiti and Jordanian stock
markets will go into effect in February 2000, said KSE Deputy
Director General Saafaq Al-Rukaibi after a meeting of the two
Arab bourses.
</P>
<P>
For his part, KSE Director General Abdallah Al-Sidrawi
expressed content over the firm steps towards the link between
the two markets, which he said had reached an advanced stage.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sidrawi said the link was "vital due to the size of the
Kuwaiti investment in Jordan and its growth over the past few
years. But he didn't give specific figures.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Deputy Chairman of the Board of Directors of the
Amman bourse, Walid Al-Najjar, said the Kuwaiti investment in
Jordan was the largest among Arab nations.
</P>
<P>
According to an official of the Jordanian stocks, investment
by non-Jordanians, especially Kuwaitis, account for some 44
percent of the total market value at the Amman bourse, which was
put at 6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Al-Najjar stressed the link between the Jordanian and Kuwaiti
bourses would benefit investors on both ends.
</P>
<P>
The KSE has already established links with the Lebanese and
Egyptian stock markets, although the results of the connection
were not made public because of the relatively short period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
