<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder, Jospin Favor EU's Rapid Eastern Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 25 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder and French premier Lionel Jospin underlined here
Saturday the importance of the European Union's rapid enlargement
toward the east.
</P>
<P>
Meeting at the eastern German town of Genshagen near Berlin,
the two leaders stressed the necessity to draw all European people
as the direct consequence of the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
"If Europe stops at Germany's border, the European thought will
go ahead without security and peace," said Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
The latest structural reform of the EU and the "Agenda 200,"
the fiscal reform package of the bloc, will be the prerequisites
of accepting more countries, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Europe has learned from the Kosovo war that those eastern
European countries must be accepted into the EU "as quickly as
possible," echoed Jospin, who was visiting Germany for a
German-Franco cultural conference.
</P>
<P>
"They (the eastern European countries) are knocking at our
borders," said Jospin.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder and Jospin called the German-Franco axis "the
flywheel for European integration," saying the latest close
relationship between Schroeder and British Prime Minister Tony
Blair would not hurt the "traditional friendship" between Germany
and France.
</P>
<P>
"The German-Franco friendship is not only a requirement of
rationality, but also a long-since matter of the heart," assured
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Both Germany and France need not apologize for pleading for
their own national interests, agreed Jospin.
</P>
<P>
The two stressed that occasional misunderstanding, or deferent
interpretation of each other's political guidance, would be "very
normal" in German-Franco ties.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder and Blair, both new leaders of left-wing parties in
their countries, were well known for sharing their view over a
pro-business social policy, which the two boasted as "the new
middle line" in their common statement issued earlier this year in
London.
</P>
<P>
The governing Socialists in France have sharply criticized the
Schroeder-Blair common statement, but Schroeder defended his
policy by saying that France, just like Germany, was faced with
deep-rooted social changes and it also needed sweeping reform.
</P>
<P>
After the cultural conference, Schroeder and Jospin held
close-door talks in Schroeder's interim chancellory in Berlin with
no detail disclosed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Join Regional Peace-Keeping Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 25 (Xinhua) --Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano has urged the country's defense force to remain alert for
possible participation of peace-keeping and security operations
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion of the 35th anniversary of the launch
of Mozambique's war for liberation from Portuguese colonial rule
on September 25, 1964, Chissano said that the forces should
continue implementing confidence-building measures to make
regional security a reality in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the armed conflicts which still plague some
member states of SADC (Southern African Development Community),
and the uncertainty as to their outcome, require the armed forces
to strengthen their operational and dissuasive capacity to
guarantee national stability and security.
</P>
<P>
However, Chissano condemned the use of force in pursuit of
political goals, saying that "we think it would be indefensible
for Africa to continue advocating the use of violence as a way to
justify any claims."
</P>
<P>
Rather, Africa should seek and find solutions for its problems
by developing and deepening dialogue and tolerance, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Chissano, the challenges the continent currently
faces are not military, but globalization, regional integration
and the HIV/AIDS pandemic.
</P>
<P>
"These are gigantic challenges that require the commitment and
the creativity of each and every Mozambican,"" he said. "We need
to strengthen our cohesion and sense of identity in order to
participate, and to confront the challenges of globalization."
</P>
<P>
The old concept of sovereignty, around which world politics had
once been organized, has been profoundly shaken, Chissano said,
adding that " financial markets, whose strength lies far from the
nation-state, weaken national control and make borders still more
porous".
</P>
<P>
"These structural changes, whose extraordinary speed causes so
much uncertainty, help create new insecurities," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the case of deeply impoverished countries such as ours,
all this is also associated with the sweep of fatal epidemics
which make evident the weakness and fragility of our
institutions," he continued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
