<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President Condemns Arms Deal with African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has condemned the illegal arms deals with the rebel groups
bent on destablizing legitimate governments in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Some American and European companies involved in supplying arms
to the anti-government groups "can't call themselves partners of
Africa," Chiluba said Friday in New York where he was attending
the United Nations Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"This is not the way to do business. This must come to an end,"
the Zambian News Agency Saturday quoted Chiluba as saying.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the International Peace Academy on the Lusaka accord
and peace prospects in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC),
the Zambian president said that many companies have adopted a
free-for-all attitude in war-torn countries by cashing in on the
situation despite many lives lost in the wars.
</P>
<P>
African people, the people in the DRC and Angola in particular,
are tired of wars and need peace and development, Chiluba noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
