<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundian President Confident in Defeating Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Burundian President Pierre
Buyoya said Saturday that Burundi has all the means to defeat the
Hutu rebels, the Rwanda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"In Burundi, we are perfectly capable to contain the rebellion
with our own forces," President Buyoya was quoted as saying after
a one-day visit to Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The president made the remarks in response to reports that
Rwanda has dispatched a lot of troops and weapons through the
northern borders of Burundi in preparation of a major joint swoop
against the Hutu armed insurgency.
</P>
<P>
The Burundian army is said to have mounted a major offensive on
the bases of the Hutu rebellion in Bujumbura Rural Province
considered the stronghold of the armed insurgency. The rebels
have stepped up attacks on capital Bujumbura in recent days.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya acknowledged that his country is faced with terrorist
attacks by the forces operating from the province, but said that
the situation is not yet out of hand.
</P>
<P>
"There is no danger of seeing the terrorists destabilizing
neither the country, nor the Bujumbura city," he noted, saying
that the rebels have no such power.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president denied that his country is risking to
slide into the Rwanda-like situation which led to the 1994
genocide.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Burundi will not degenerate into
mass-killings, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya arrived in Rwandan capital Kigali on Friday morning and
immediately held talks with Rwandan Pasteur Bizimungu and his
Vice- President Paul Kagame.
</P>
<P>
Their discussions focused mainly on the situation in the Great
Lakes region and the stalled Burundi peace process, Buyoya said.
</P>
<P>
A week-long session of Burundi peace talks ended in Tanzania's
northern town of Arusha last Sunday without clinching a peace deal
to end the bloody conflicts in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
But delegates at the talks have agreed to meet again in late
October.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Burundian president was in Kampala on a one-day
visit during which he met with his Ugandan counterpart Yoweri
Museveni and discussed the same issues.
</P>
<P>
The six-year ethnic violence in Burundi has allegedly claimed
more than 150,000 people, mostly civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
