<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-25 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Ready to Work with U.S. Oil Firms: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Saturday declared
its readiness to cooperate with international oil companies
including U.S. companies to supply Iraq's oil sector with
the required oil equipment and spare parts.
</P>
<P>
Oil Undersecretary Taha Hammoud Mousa made the remarks at an
inauguration ceremony for an oil and gas technology exhibition
currently held in Baghdad with the participation of 56 Arab and
foreign oil companies.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the message hints Iraq's
flexibility in dealing with U.S. oil companies in the future.
</P>
<P>
In the past, Baghdad refused to do business with hostile
countries, referring to the U.S. and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Iraqi official accused the U.S. and British
representatives at the U.N. Sanctions Committee for hampering the
endorsement of Iraq's contracts on purchasing spare parts for its
oil sector under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iraq had only received 60 million U.S. dollars
worth of oil equipment and spare parts out of a total of 600
million dollars of contracts it signed with foreign companies in
the fourth and fifth phases of the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food deal now in its sixth phase, Iraq is
allowed to export limited amount of oil in every six months to buy
food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies for its people
reeling under the nine-year-old U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was allowed by the U.N. Security Council to import 600
million dollars of oil equipment and spare parts in the fourth
and fifth phases of the deal to rehabilitate its dilapidated oil
installations.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has long accused the U.S. and British envoys at the
Sanctions Committee of deliberately putting on hold many of its
contracts, saying the humanitarian program has failed to
alleviate the sufferings of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Mousa said he hoped that the participating companies would
supply Iraq with high quality oil equipment and offer competitive
prices.
</P>
<P>
He said the fact that the event has drawn so many oil companies
shows their eagerness to work with Iraq in the future, adding that
most of the companies had signed contracts with Iraq before.
</P>
</TEXT>
