<HEADLINE> Thailand on Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- To meet the challenges
of globalization and take the most advantages from its benefits,
the international community must join hands to promote
globalization with a human face, Thailand said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the general debate of the 54th session of the United
Nations General Assembly, Thailand's Minister for Foreign Affairs
Surin Pitsuwan said "globalization with a human face" is not a new
idea.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has spoken about it, and the
United Nations, particularly the United Nations Development
Program, has long been a proponent of this concept, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
He said globalization should be ensured to lead to, among other
things:
</P>
<P>
-- Greater equity among peoples and nations,
</P>
<P>
-- The easing of social tensions and strengthening of
communities,
</P>
<P>
-- the inclusion of a greater number of economies as
stakeholders and co-partners in the building of the global
economy,
</P>
<P>
-- Declining poverty and reduction of the income gap between
the very rich and the very poor,
</P>
<P>
-- Enhanced protection and preservation of the environment,
</P>
<P>
-- Greater protection and promotion of human rights and
fundamental freedoms,
</P>
<P>
-- And, perhaps most importantly and very simply, a better life
for all peoples.
</P>
<P>
"Joining hands to promote globalization with a human face is a
distinct contribution to promoting human security. The United
Nations is already playing a leadership role in realizing this
goal at a global level. But the United Nations cannot do this
alone. It needs to forge a partnership with non-governmental
sector, especially the private sector and civil society and other
international organizations," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
