<HEADLINE> Russia Continues Air Strikes on Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian warplanes raided the
breakaway republic of Chechnya for the third day Saturday,
knocking out television and mobile telephone networks, said
Russian media reports.
</P>
<P>
"The television center has ceased to exist," Air Force
commander Anatoly Kornukov said, referring to the television
station in Grozny, the regional capital.
</P>
<P>
He said the raids would continue "until the job of killing off
the fighters, their bases and sites supporting them is
completed."
</P>
<P>
The latest raids further targeted Chechnya's already largely
crippled oil installations. The head of Grozny's refinery said his
facility, working sporadically for months, had been shut down
completely.
</P>
<P>
Kornukov said the Russian air force had been 80 percent
accurate in more than 1,700 air missions in the past three weeks
using Su-24 and Su-25 jets. More than 2,000 rebels had been
killed, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the guerrillas remained well equipped. "There is still
work to be done," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kornukov said federal forces would stick to "pinpoint attacks"
on bases and other sites used by the rebels and there were no
plans for "carpet bombing" and no need to enlist long-range
bombers.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated that there would be no attacks on civilian
targets.
</P>
<P>
There were different reports of casualties in the raids. While
the Interfax news agency said seven people had died in the latest
raids, the RIA agency put the toll at three.
</P>
<P>
A Chechen official speaking in London Friday said nearly 300
had died in two weeks of Russian military action in the region.
</P>
<P>
Moscow insists that its air force was only targeting bases,
arms depots and other facilities used by the Islamic rebels that
twice infiltrated the neighboring Daghestan republic and were
believed to be behind several apartment block explosions that
killed more than 300 people in Moscow and other major Russian
cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
