<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK on U.N. Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Without enhancing the
authority of the General Assembly and without early restructuring
of the Security Council, the United Nations would be unable to
meet the demands of a rapidly changing situation and cope with new
challenges, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) said
here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the general debate of the 54th session of the
General Assembly, DPRK Minister for Foreign Affairs Paek Nam Sun
said the authority of the General Assembly where all member states
are represented and interact democratically on an equal footing
should be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
"If the General Assembly is empowered to deliberate on crucial
issues such as ensuring international peace and security and
finally examines important resolutions adopted by the Security
Council concerning sanctions and the use of force, this will be
conducive to ensuring fairness in the U.N. activities and
preventing high-handness and arbitrariness by individual
countries," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council should be reformed in such a way as to
make all regions equally represented in its composition and ensure
full transparency in its activities. In this regard, we oppose,
under any circumstances, the permanent membership of a defeated
nation which has not liquidated its past crimes," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are of the view that the proposal put forward by member
countries of the non-aligned movement to first increase
non-permanent seats, which is relatively easy to be agreed upon at
this stage, deserves sincere consideration," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
