<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Tourism To Grow 4.2 Percent in Next Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- World tourism will have an
average growth of 4.2 percent between 2000 and 2010 as forecast by
the World Tourism Organization (WTO) here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The WTO started the same day in the Chilean capital the
preparations for its 13th General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is attended by more than 1,000 delegates from 131
countries that will discuss the conservation of natural and
cultural resources, as well as the impact of the new information
and marketing technologies of the touristic business.
</P>
<P>
WTO General Secretary Francesco Frangialli said at the
preparatory forum that it is possible that "internal tourism will
be 10 times bigger than the international tourism in the year
2020."
</P>
<P>
The biggest growth of touristic activity will occur in the
developing countries of Asia, Latin America and the Middle East,
said Frangialli.
</P>
<P>
He said that 635 million tourists were registered in 1998 all
over the world and that income, excluding international
transportation, was 439 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"This means that tourism exported 1.2 billion dollars every
day," said the WTO secretary general.
</P>
<P>
Frangialli also explained that tourist income represented last
year 8 percent of the world commerce of services, which puts this
activity among the sectors of the biggest importance, together
with oil and motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Regarding South America, he said that the region had more than
18 million arrivals. Tourism grew 8.2 percent in the last 10 years
in South America, doubling the world growth rate, which was 4.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
Frangialli said Chile earned about 1 billion dollars in 1998,
receiving 1.8 million foreign visitors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yuhuatai Monument to Martyrs Repaired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The Yuhuatai Monument to
Martyrs, a sacred site for commemorating those who participated
land sacrificed their lives in China's revolution, opened to the
public today after being repaired.
</P>
<P>
Visitors can now see more than 1,100 items of revolutionary
relics inside the monument, more than before the repairs. The
number of revolutionary martyrs whose images and records exhibited
has also increased to 1,519.
</P>
<P>
Advanced computer technology also has been introduced to add
visibility and attraction to the exhibitors, a local source said.
</P>
<P>
After the founding of new China in 1949, the city of Nanjing,
home of the monument, created some highly valued carvings which
include group sculptures of revolutionary martyrs on the Yuhuatai
Monument and sculptures in the memorial hall of the victims of the
1937 Nanjing Massacre.
</P>
<P>
The monument has become an important base for nationwide
patriotic education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
