<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Push Ahead Strategic Restructuring of SOEs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- China will continue the
strategic restructuring of its State-owned enterprises in a move
to enhance their competitiveness, says "The Decision of the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China on Major Issues
Concerning the Reform and Development of State-owned Enterprises".
</P>
<P>
According to the Decision, which was issued here today, China
will give support to a handful of enterprises that must be
monopolized by the State to help them play their due role.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises that have considerable strength in competitive
fields should accelerate their development by attracting
investment from different sectors. Enterprises that do have a
market for their products but are suffering from an excessive
burden and managerial difficulties should regroup their assets and
readjust their structure in the forms of merger and association.
</P>
<P>
Bankruptcy and closure have to be conducted for enterprises
that can not find any market for their products, have been
suffering from long-time losses, and are not expected to turn loss
into profit, as well as those that have been wasting resources,
are technologically backward, are manufacturing poor-quality
products, and have caused severe pollution, the Decision says.
</P>
<P>
Efforts should be made to foster powerful and competitive large
enterprises and enterprise groups, some of which could be turned
into trans-regional, trans-industrial, trans-ownership and
transnational large enterprise groups. Their superiority in
capital management and technological renovation should be made
full use of, so as to turn them into pillars of the national
economy and the major players in international competition, it
points out.
</P>
<P>
Active support will be given to small and medium-sized
enterprises, especially hi-tech ones. Small state-owned
enterprises are encouraged to adopt various forms to invigorate
themselves. Those forms include regrouping, association, merger,
leasing, contract-based management, shareholding, and sale.
</P>
<P>
In the process of the strategic regrouping of state-owned
enterprises, the role of market mechanism should be brought into
full play, while economic, legal and necessary administrative
means should be applied, the document says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
