<HEADLINE> Iranian Parliament Demands Stricter Supervision of Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The conservative-dominated
Majlis (parliament) of Iran on Sunday called on the government to
exert stricter supervision over the local media in line with
Islamic rules.
</P>
<P>
Some 170 members of the Majlis signed a letter to President
Mohammad Khatami, calling on him to "pay more attention to the
cultural environment" of the country, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The legislators accused "some segments of the press" for making
"insults to sanctities and violations of Islamic rules."
</P>
<P>
Amid the power struggle between hard-liners who dominate the
judiciary and the parliament, on one side, and the reformists
represented by Khatami on the other, a number of pro-reformists
newspapers were banned by the conservatives recently for
publishing "hostile articles."
</P>
<P>
The letter demanded that the Ministry of Culture and Islamic
Guidance, the body in charge of the country's cultural affairs,
provide necessary tools to "prevent insults to Islamic principles
and sanctities through stricter supervision over the ministry's
performance."
</P>
<P>
"Violations of values and insults to religious principles and
sanctities ... are intolerable" in a state "whose duty is to
enforce Islamic rules and regulations," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
"Those who neglect warnings and cautions" of religious scholars
and the supreme leader Ayatollah Khamenei are "acting against the
interests of the Islamic system" as well as the ideals of late
supreme leader Ayatollah Khomeini and Khamenei, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Majlis representatives expected the authorities in charge
of cultural affairs to exercise a stricter supervision over such
activities, the letter concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
