<HEADLINE> Qatar's Coup Suspects Put on Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 29 (Xinhua) -- Qatar's Supreme Criminal
Court on Sunday began the trial of Sheikh Hamad Bin Jassem Bin
Hamad Al-Thani, the suspected mastermind of a 1996 coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
Two other suspects, who were identified as Ghanem Saleh
Al-Kawari and Mete'b Twaim Al-Meri, were also brought to the
court.
</P>
<P>
The public prosecutor charged the three with attempting to oust
Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa Al-Thani in collaboration with a
foreign country and to leak state military secrets.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hamad Bin Jassem was accused of masterminding the foiled
coup, in which he "hired a number of individuals and mapped out a
plan to carry out the coup operation, brought arms to the country,
and continued his bid against the Qatari regime after the failed
attempt on February 13, 1996."
</P>
<P>
The three denied all the charges, according to the Kuwait News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
After debates, the supreme judge adjourned the session to
October 3 to enable the defendants' attorney to ponder files and
statements of the suspects, the report said. A sentence in the
case is expected early next year.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hamad Bin Jassem, Qatar's former police chief and former
minister of economy and trade, was captured by Qatar's secret
agents on July 23 in a foreign country, whose name the report did not
disclose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
