<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Build Up Highly Qualified Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- To meet the needs of
establishing a modern enterprise system and to survive and develop
in fierce competition, China's state-owned enterprises (SOEs) must
build up their highly qualified management and nurture a big batch
of excellent entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
The Decision of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) on Major Issues Concerning the Reform and Development
of State-Owned Enterprises, which was made public today, points
out that the management of SOEs is generally good and have made
important contributions to the reform and development of the
enterprises. However, the trend of building up a socialist market
economy has imposed new demands to SOE managers.
</P>
<P>
The reform of personnel system of SOEs should be deepened. The
CPC must manage and supervise its SOE cadres. The Central
Committee and local committees of the Party must strengthen
management over the operation of SOEs that hold the lifeline of
the state security and national economy.
</P>
<P>
They should probe for new mechanisms that conform to the modern
corporate system in personnel management, combine organizational
appraisal and recommendation with market mechanisms and public
applications, and combine the principle of the Party administering
officials with the right of board of directors to select managers
as well as managers exercising personnel powers according to law,
the Decision says.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a talent market for business managers must be
established and greater efforts made to create conditions for
building a social environment conducive to the healthy growth of
managers and entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
The Decision points out that a system should be established to
encourage SOE managers' brilliant performance and to curb their
irresponsible conducts. The managers' incomes should be linked
with their performance. Managers should not only get due material
rewards, they should also receive due honors for their devotion. A
few enterprises have tried some distribution modes including the
annual salary system for managers. This can be further
experimented to gather experiences but should not be taken as an
example for enterprises to follow indiscriminately. There should a
system to standardize the allocating of salaries to managers and
that system should be transparent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more work should be done to increase supervision
over managers in areas such as use of funds, production and
management, income distribution, use of personnel and self-
discipline. Managers who fail to follow relevant laws and
regulations and cause heavy losses to their enterprises should be
duly punished and they should be removed from their posts, nor
should they be transferred to work as a leader elsewhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
