<HEADLINE> Russian Air Force Continues Pounding Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian fighter jets continued
air raids on the breakaway republic of Chechnya for a fourth day
Sunday, dropping missiles and bombs on terrorist strongholds and
facilities, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Oktyabrsk district of Grozny, the regional capital, again
came under attack, Tass said, quoting the press center of federal
forces in Dagestan, a republic bordering Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
In the past 24 hours, federal jets bombed terrorist camps,
communication and provision bases along the administrative border
between Chechnya and Dagestan, Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 200 armored military vehicles backed by helicopters
and gunships advanced to the border with Chechnya from Ingush,
another Russian province in the North Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
Their main task is to prevent Chechen terrorists from
penetrating into the republic of Dagestan, Tass said, quoting
Ingushi Interior Ministry spokeswoman Madina Khadziyeva.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to 1994, when the Chechen war just started and the
Ingushi population attempted to block federal troops from
advancing to Chechnya, the local people are quiet this time about
the deployment of federal troops around, the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
"The people are tired of bandit raids and kidnapping from the
territory of Chechnya,," she said.
</P>
<P>
As the air raids over Chechnya continues, the flow of refugees
to Ingush has been increasing steadily. Two tent camps were set up,
but they could only house 500 people, far from enough to
accommodating the 40,000 refugees already there.
</P>
<P>
The latest federal assaults, the fiercest since the end of
1994-1996 Chechen war, came after repeated incursions by Islamic
rebels from Chechnya to Dagestan and several apartment building
blasts that killed more than 300 people in Moscow and other major
Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has been moving federal troops and special police units
to Chechnya's border with neighboring republics. Russia has also
carried out air strikes on the Grozny airport, arms depots, mobile
telephone networks and radio and television broadcast facilities
that believed to be at the service of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
While authorities insist that there is no plan to launch a
ground campaign in Chechnya, Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said
on Sunday that he would not rule out such a possibility.
</P>
<P>
"There are several variants of the plan which will be
implemented depending on the situation," Tass quoted Sergeyev as
saying during a visit to the Burdenko military hospital where
soldiers and officers wounded in Dagestan are recovering.
</P>
<P>
"The main aim of all the plans is to eliminate bandits," the
minister said, stressing the importance "to create a considerably
deep security zone (around Chechnya)."
</P>
<P>
He praised the servicemen for their "courage and heroism" in
fighting Islamic insurrectionists in Dagestan. There have been one
hundred and five servicemen killed and 306 wounded in the fighting.
</P>
</TEXT>
