<HEADLINE> Pinochet Extradition Hearing to Open on Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The formal hearing on whether
former Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet should be sent to stand
trial in Spain is scheduled to open in a British court on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming hearing is to consider whether the retired
general should be extradited to Spain to face trial for alleged
human rights abuses during his 17-year iron-fisted rule, which
ended in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The session is set for five days and the decision could come
within two weeks of its close. After the decision is made, either
side can appeal and the judicial marathon may run months or years
more.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, who is 83 years old and suffers some serious
illnesses, was arrested in a London hospital last October after a
Spanish judge accused him of responsibility to the deaths and
disappearances of 3,000 people. The Spanish judge wanted him to be
extradited to Spain to face the charges.
</P>
<P>
His case has been in and out of British court on various legal
points ever since. A lot of speculations on what will happen to
the retired general come and go every month here in London.
</P>
<P>
A local report said that if the court next week rules against
Pinochet, the general might abandon further appeals and instead
ask Home Secretary Jack Straw to block his extradition on
humanitarian grounds, given his advanced age and frail health.
</P>
<P>
Another floated speculation is that Pinochet would go to Spain
voluntarily in hope of winning his case there or striking a deal
with Spanish prosecutors or the government.
</P>
<P>
But one of his Spanish lawyers said this week he had advised
Pinochet against leaving Britain before appeals were exhausted.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet is not expected to attend the trial planned to be held
from Monday on in the Victorian-era Bow Street Magistrates' Court
in London's Covent Garden. He has to be present only for the
decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
