<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Plans to Launches GSLV Early Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Indian planned to launch
its geosynchronous satellite launch vehicle (GSLV) in January,
2000, and develop its own cryogenic engine in the first quarter,
the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
PTI quoted Dr. G. Madhavan Nair, newly-appointed director of
the Vikram Sarabhal Space Center (VSSC), as saying that the first
phase of cryogenic engine would be used in the second or third
launch of the GSLV in 2000 or 2002.
</P>
<P>
The GSLV, which was now capable of carrying satellites weighing
upto 25 tones, would be improved to carry satellites upto to 36
tones in the orbit.
</P>
<P>
The decision to develop India's own cryogenic engine, which at
present supplied by Russia, was made in 1992 and got government
approval in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Nair said in Thiruvananthapuram, 2,800 kms south of here, that
Indian scientists had been working on the project ever since in
order to take the country to a position of self-reliance in the
space sector.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that India's achievements in space sector was unique
among developing countries and pictures from its remote sensing
satellites were the finest.
</P>
<P>
Nair disclosed that GSLV had an estimated project cost of 13
billion rupees (300 million U.S. dollars) and a three-stage launch
system with three core motors.
</P>
<P>
VSSC, based in Thiruvananthapuram, was using 99 percent
technology of its own and the excess workload had forced it to
share some of its works with some private and public sector
institutions, Nair said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
