<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Lists Progress in His Country </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo said he had done a lot to restore hope in the country and
win the respect of the international community since he took
office in May this year, the Guardian newspaper reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The president, speaking at a press conference during his trip
to the United Nations in New York on Saturday, said before his
elected civilian government came to power, Nigeria gave a combined
image of military dictatorship, a corruption-ridden,
crime-infested and ethnic-strife rampant society, and a collapsing
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The image is no longer valid after his four months in the
saddle, and Nigeria is different from what it was in the past,
said Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
On corruption, Obasanjo noted that while Nigeria for two
consecutive years led the corruption index of Transparency
International, the situation on the ground now is no longer the
same.
</P>
<P>
"I will be fooling myself to say corruption has been eradicated
in Nigeria," said the president. "There is no where in the world
where there is no corruption. But corruption was a way of life in
Nigeria. We are trying to change that. We cannot give ourselves
full marks yet. But we are on the way."
</P>
<P>
He said the police would be retrained, reorganized and
adequately equipped to confront the rising wave of crime.
</P>
<P>
The president cited improvement in power supply as an
indication of the seriousness of his government to confront the
problems, adding that in one year the problem of frequent power
cut will be a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo stated that the orientation of his government is that
of " private sector-led economy."
</P>
<P>
"Our responsibility is to provide the conducive environment for
 investment to come in," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
