<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptians Tend to Vote for Mubarak's Fourth Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian voters cast their
ballots on Sunday in a referendum certain to endorse parliament
nomination of President Hosni Mubarak for a fourth term.
</P>
<P>
The poll started at 8:00 local time (0500 GMT) and will end at
17:00 (14:00 GMT). Results are expected on Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the polling station in the El Oukaf Secondary School in
Cairo's Mohandesin District, hundreds of voters gathered on the
school playground, chanting pro-Mubarak slogans.
</P>
<P>
"Yes to Mubarak!" "Mubarak, we love you!" "We would like to
sacrifice for you!" chanted the voters, holding high a large
portrait of Mubarak and banner supporting the president.
</P>
<P>
"We support Mubarak's leadership as he has done a lot to
improve the life of the Egyptian people during the past 18 years,"
Esam Hosni, a preparatory school English teacher, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"Mubarak is leading the country in a process to better its
economic landscape by carrying out reform programs and large-scale
irrigation projects such as the Toshka scheme in the south," Hosni
said.
</P>
<P>
He said he will vote for the president, "one hundred percent."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was first elected president in 1981 after the
assassination of former president Anwar Sadat. He was re-elected
twice in 1987 and 1993. In the past referendums, Mubarak received
more than 95 percent "yes" votes.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's constitution does not allow for a direct presidential
election. Instead, the parliament, the People's Assembly,
nominates one candidate for the presidency. A referendum must then
be held to endorse the nomination.
</P>
<P>
The parliament, which is dominated by Mubarak's National
Democratic Party, chose him for a fourth six-year term in
July. The voters are asked to say "yes" or "no" to the nominee.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has set up a total of 40,907 polling stations in the 26
governorates for about 24 million eligible voters of the country's
64 million people.
</P>
<P>
Three hours after the polls opened, Mubarak cast a ballot with
his wife Suzanne and two sons at a school in the posh Cairo suburb
of Heliopolis.
</P>
<P>
The government devoted considerably to secure "yes" votes for
Mubarak. Portraits of the president and banners supporting him fly
from government buildings and along the main streets in the
capital. The government provided free rides for the day on all
state-owned vehicles. The major pro-government newspapers,
Al-Ahram and Al Gomhuria, emblazoned their front pages with color
photos of Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has been keen on helping advance the Arab-Israeli peace
talks and launched an economic privatization program which has
helped Egypt maintain one of the best economic performances in the
Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
