<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Defends Asian Women's Volleyball Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion China
encountered a stiff challenge from Japan before winning the title
for the seventh time in a row on Sunday at the 10th Asian Women's
Volleyball Championship.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese players defeated their Japanese counterparts 25-19,
20-25,25-23 and 25-19.
</P>
<P>
"We have completed our first goal of the year, winning the
title and the berth in the World Cup," said Hu Jin, head coach of
the Chinese team.
</P>
<P>
He said the next goal for the Chinese is to gain the right to
play in the 2000 Olympic Games next year by finishing among the
top three places at the up-coming World Cup women's tournament in
Japan in November.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team got to a flying start by resorting to varied
tactics with a string of changes and powerful spikes and kept
their dominance on the court in the first set, winning 25-19.
</P>
<P>
But the second set saw the spirited Japanese turning the table
with a good teamwork and fast attacks. After taking the second set
25-20, the Japanese continued their dominance in the beginning of
the third set, leading at 18-14.
</P>
<P>
After a time-out, the world and Olympic silver medalists
Chinese struggled to find their powerful spikes and fast attacks
and run away with the set at 25-23.
</P>
<P>
The fourth set proved to be an easy work for the Chinese, who
kept the rhythm with their superiority over the net before taking
the set and the match 25-19.
</P>
<P>
This is the ninth meeting between China and Japan this year
with the Chinese winning all the matches.
</P>
<P>
South Korea ranked second in the tournament by outplaying
Thailand on Sunday with a score of 25-9, 25-19 and 25-15.
</P>
<P>
The top two finishers of the tournament will represent Asian in
the World Cup tournament in November. Japan, which finished third,
get an automatic berth in the World Cup. Thailand was fourth in
the event.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yongmei of China won the MVP award while the best spikier
award went to South Korea's Ku Min Jung. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
