<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Taking Measures to Reduce SOE Burdens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- To gradually solve problems
of China's state-owned enterprises (SOEs) such as high asset-to-
liability rate, capital shortage and heavy social burden is of
utmost importance in their reform and development, according to a
decision of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
These problems should be solved step by step through various
means in consideration of the country's current macro-economic and
financial situation, says the Decision of the CPC Central
Committee on Major Issues Concerning the Reform and Development of
State-Owned Enterprises, which was published today.
</P>
<P>
The decision puts forward the following measures:
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese banks should have more reserves for writing off the
non-performing loans caused by the merger and bankruptcy of SOEs
and closure of a number of dried-up coal mines, especially in key
industries. Incentives will be given to encourage the merger
between state-owned and collectively-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
-- Major SOEs, currently debt-ridden but having potentials,
should solve the problem of high asset-to-liability rate by debt-
to-equity swap, together with the state banks' current reform on
handling non-performing loans and with the help of financial asset
management firms.
</P>
<P>
-- Accumulation of funds through direct means should be
enhanced. SOEs which already met the qualifications for listing
may raise funds in domestic and overseas capital markets, and the
proportion of public shares under current circulation should be
increased. Other SOEs may prepare for the listing by debt
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
State-owned and state holding enterprises will be allowed to
participate in the allocation of new shares. A number of high-
yielding and promising state holding listed companies will be
picked out to reduce the state capital proportion, and the capital
thus raised will be used for other SOEs' reform and development.
</P>
<P>
The system of stock issuance and listing should be further
improved to promote the healthy development of China's securities
market.
</P>
<P>
-- With the government approval, unlisted SOEs can acquire cash
by transferring their land-use right or fixed assets for
increasing working capital and reducing debts as well as their own
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
-- The government policies on the interest rate should be
strictly followed to alleviate SOEs' burdens.
</P>
<P>
-- Large SOEs with the capability of paying off debts are
allowed to issue corporate bonds with government approval and
after appraisal by intermediate agencies, and some enterprises are
permitted issue corporate bonds outside China as well.
</P>
<P>
-- SOEs will gradually break away from the social welfare
responsibility (for running their own schools, hospitals and other
services) in an effort to reduce their social burden.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0091 </DOCNO>
