<HEADLINE> Two Australia Law Firms Approved to Open Offices in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 26 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Justice today
granted two Australian law firms approval to establish branch
agencies in China, bringing the total number of foreign law firms
in China to 81.
</P>
<P>
Today's move represents a quick response to President Jiang
Zemin's pledge during his visit to Australia earlier this month
that the ratification of two more Australian law offices in China
would mark another step in the progress of Sino-Australian
economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Deacons Graham &AMP; James and the Minter Ellison law firms
will locate their offices in China's largest city of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Along with the 81 foreign law firms from 10 countries, there
are 26 others from Hong Kong who have opened branch offices in
China, said Gao Changli, minister of justice, at today's ceremony
for issuing certificates of approval to the two Australian firms.
</P>
<P>
He said that among the top 50 law firms in the world, over a
half have opened branches offices in China, and many of the rest
have made application to do so.
</P>
<P>
Gao pledged that the Ministry of Justice will, as always, do
its best to help more overseas law firms set up branches in the
country for better services to foreign investors in China, and
China's foreign trade and economic cooperation with other
countries.
</P>
<P>
The minister is working on relevant regulations governing the
ratification and operations of foreign law firm branch offices in
China, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China's 8,400 law firms were employing
over 110,000 lawyers by the end of last year. Seven Chinese law
firms have established agencies in foreign countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
