<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading Israeli newspapers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- After meeting with French President Jacques Chirac in Paris
Saturday, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat called on the
international community for support to ensure that the latest
Israeli-Palestinian agreement is followed through. Meanwhile, the
Israeli-Palestinian committee on the safe-passage route between
Gaza and the West Bank will meet Sunday to try to iron out the
remaining differences and finalize the protocol.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Syria suffered a diplomatic blow when it failed to keep
other Arab countries from attending a multilateral meeting with
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy in New York Friday. The
absence of Syria and Lebanon got more attention than the presence
of 11 Arab countries and 5 countries from the Persian Gulf, some
of which have no diplomatic relations with Israel. Levy said after
the meeting that the major significance of the event "was in that
it expressed the commitment of the Arab world and the countries of
the Persian Gulf and the Maghreb to the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- A crisis over the government funding of Shas' school system
hung on Saturday night as Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Education
Minister Yossi Sarid failed to reach an agreement with the
Shas. Despite marathon efforts which began late Thursday, Shas
denied compromise proposals from Barak and Sarid, which include
the demand that Shas fire head of its school system, who is under
investigation by police for fraud charge.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Musa Damri, a 56-year-old resident of Silwan in East
Jerusalem, Saturday shot dead two of his three grown daughters
and seriously wounded the third one before committing
suicide. Police investigators discovered that the father, a
retired bus driver, had a history of physically abusing his
daughters and that he often complained that they did not treat
him with respect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
