<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Folk Show Popular in National Minorities Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- A long bamboo rod with
umbrella-shaped decorations and jingle bells at top was vertically
tossed into the air from the performer's tiptoe and a second later
it fell upright on his forehead, arousing loud cheering and
applause from the spectators in the gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
"Zhongfan", a traditional Chinese folk show is being displayed
as one of the demonstration events at China's National Games for
Traditional Sports of Minority Nationalities in Beijing. And it
is becoming one of the most welcomed events at the week-long Games
opened here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In the ten-minute acrobatic action, the performer props "
Zhongfan" up from or let it fall on the forehead, nose, jaws,
shoulder, elbow, thumb, little finger or even tiptoe and,
occasionally, tosses it from one another without even using their
hands. It could be performed individually or by a team of up to
five members.
</P>
<P>
Dating back as early as in ancient China's Tang Dynasty (618-
907), "Zhongfan" was originally an oriflamme in the army or
present as part of the royal guard of honor. Mongolian tribe
soldiers usually perform it as an exercise or just for fun.
</P>
<P>
It was later developed into a folk show among such minority
nationalities in China as Mongolia, Manchu and Hui. The oriflamme
was transformed into the current shape to make it the performance
more difficult and more entertaining as well.
</P>
<P>
The "Zhongfan" for performance now weighs about 25 kilograms,
with the bamboo rod some 12 centimeters in diameter and 10 meters
long.
</P>
<P>
"As a Chinese quintessence, it should be cherished and further
promoted to make it more prosperous," said famous performer Chang
Quandong. A member of the Mongolia minority nationality himself,
Chang, 54, leads a Beijing-based Zhongfan League, one of the most
famous Zhongfan clubs in the country.
</P>
<P>
Chang's team members are all from his family, including his son
and nephews. He said he wishes to set up a school to teach "
Zhongfan" performance.
</P>
<P>
"I've been interviewed by the China Central Television and it
will be broadcast tomorrow," said a proud and delighted Chang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
