<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- A four-day exhibition by 180 Thai firms opened
Saturday in Sharjah, the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
On display are a wide-range of products including ready-made
clothes, textiles, foodstuff, building materials, electronic
appliances and decorative materials.
</P>
<P>
The UAE is Thailand's top trading partner in the Middle East,
with bilateral trade volume totaling more than 1.26 billion
U.S. dollars in 1998, and volume in the first seven month of this
year reaching 741.7 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi economists and businessmen have urged the
advisory committee of the supreme economic council "to evaluate
the country's financial and economic policies" in a bid to
restructure Saudi Arabia's economy and control expenditure.
</P>
<P>
They listed such pressing issues as top priorities for the
council: economic growth, privatization of a large number of
state-owned enterprises, reducing unnecessary public expenditures,
rationalization of state expenses, and supporting the private
sector to improve the country's economic performance, the Arab
daily Al Hayat reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran has ordered four container ships from South
Korean ship builders, said Managing Director of the Islamic
Republic Shipping Line (IRSL) Ahad Mohammadi on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Each container ship, to be delivered by the year 2000, has a
displacement capacity of 3,300 containers and is worth 34.5
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The IRSL has signed an agreement with the Bandar Abbas-based
Persian Gulf Shipbuilding Firm to build six container ships with
capacities of 2,000 to 2,5000 containers, the first of which will
be delivered after 28 months.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said his company shipped over 3 million tons of
cargoes last year (March 1998 to March 1999).
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabia is one of the biggest consumers of
computers and Internet-related programs in the Middle East and is
the fastest growing market in the world, said Michael Lacome,
Executive Chairman of the U.S. computer giant Microsoft in Europe,
Africa and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has seen an annual growth rate in sales of 25
percent, said the official.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft is planning to establish a training center for
computer users in Saudi government departments and educational
institutions to engage in scientific research at King Abdul Aziz
Science and Technology city, the Egyptian daily Alam Al Yom
reported Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
