<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Urges Land Use Policy to Prevent Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
Sunday called on the congress to legislate a national land use
policy in order to minimize consequences of earthquake disasters.
</P>
<P>
Speaking for the administration, National Defense Secretary
Orlando Mercado said in an interview here that a national land use
policy could give all concerned sectors a "map" of areas
pinpointed by authorities as prone to earthquake or landslide.
</P>
<P>
"When we have a map, we will have a sort of a plan that we use
when we build a house. But for the past several decades, we have
been using lands indiscriminately," Mercado said.
</P>
<P>
Mercado, who is also chairman of the National Disaster
Coordinating Council (NDCC), said the need for a land use policy
was made clear as early as August, when a landslide destroyed
several houses at the Cherry Hills subdivision in Antipolo City,
Manila.
</P>
<P>
He said developers must know which lands are safe for
development into residential or industrial areas and which lands
be developed for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The national land use policy is a long-term solution that would
complement the government's program to achieve food security and
disaster preparedness, the official said.
</P>
<P>
"We really want a long-term solution. The first thing that we
should do is to push a bill in the congress," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mercado said that as part of its program for disaster
preparedness, the NDCC, in coordination with the Metro Manila
Development Authority (MMDA) and Local Government Units (LGUs), is
now conducting earthquake and fire drills.
</P>
<P>
As an earthquake-prone country, the Philippines experiences at
least five earthquakes a day, but most of them are too weak to be
felt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
