<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 07:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptians Begin to Vote on Mubarak's Fourth Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptians began early Sunday to
cast ballots in a referendum which is believed to be certain to
endorse parliament nomination of President Hosni Mubarak for a
fourth term.
</P>
<P>
The poll started at 8:00 local time (0500 GMT) and will end at
17:00 (14:00 GMT). The result is expected on Monday.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 voters entered a polling station in a school in
the Mohandesin District when the voting process kicked off. Some
of them arrived there by free rides provided by the government on
all state-owned transportation for the day.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has set up a total of 40,907 polling stations in the 26
governorates across Egypt for about 24 million eligible voters of
the country's 64 million people to cast their ballots in the
yes-no referendum.
</P>
<P>
Portraits of Mubarak and banners supporting him fly from
government buildings and along the main streets in the capital,
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
In the past referendums, Mubarak received more than 95 percent
"yes" votes.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's constitution does not allow for a direct presidential
election. Instead, the parliament, the People's Assembly,
nominates one candidate for the presidency. A referendum must then
be held to endorse the nomination.
</P>
<P>
The parliament, which is dominated by Mubarak's National
Democratic Party, chose him for a fourth six-year term in
July. The voters are asked to say "yes" or "no" to the nominee.
</P>
<P>
After the assassination of President Anwar Sadat in 1981,
Mubarak, the then vice president, became president. He was
re-elected in 1987 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has been keen on helping advance the Arab-Israeli
peace talks and unleashed an economic privatization program which
has helped Egypt maintain one of the best economic performances in
the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
