<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Public Hospitals Lack TB Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The tuberculosis (TB) drugs
are often in short supply in most Zambian public hospitals and
clinics, Sunday Mail newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The report also revealed that while the University Teaching
Hospital in Lusaka, the biggest hospital in Zambia and even in
southern Africa, and other public health institutions suffer acute
shortage of TB drugs, private pharmacies have almost all types of
TB drugs.
</P>
<P>
A source at the Central Board of Health maintained that the
shortage at public hospitals was a result of insufficient drugs
being brought into the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the source declined to comment on allegations of
pilfering of the TB drugs from public hospitals to private
pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
Sunday Times of Zambia newspaper reported that more than 4,000
TB cases were detected last year in Kitwe district of Copperbelt
Province alone, and over 600 people of them died.
</P>
<P>
The district has diagnosed more than 2,000 people with the
disease so far this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
