<HEADLINE> Fresh Fighting Kills 12 Tamil Rebels in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Defense Ministry
said Sunday that its troops killed 12 Tamil rebels in the latest
conflicts in the north of the country as security has been
tightened ahead of the first anniversary of a major battle.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that troops Saturday killed
seven Tamil rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE)
in two separate incidents in the northern Wanni region.
</P>
<P>
It said troops killed four LTTE guerrillas in the early hours
of Sunday in the Wanni region, the main battlefield between the
troops and LTTE rebels who have been fighting a 16-year-old war
for a Tamil homeland in Sri Lanka's north and east.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said troops Saturday sniped and killed one more
rebel south of Paranthan in the Jaffna region.
</P>
<P>
The latest fighting came as the warring sides are going to
observe the first anniversary of a major battle in the Wanni
region.
</P>
<P>
During the battle starting from September 27 last year, the
government troops recaptured Mankulam town but lost Kilinochchi,
which is just below the neck of the northern Jaffna peninsula, the
former stronghold of LTTE rebels.
</P>
<P>
The loss of Kilinochchi forced the government to suspend one of
its longest military operations which had been launched in May
1997 to open a land route to Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
Officials said troops were on alert in all sensitive areas in
the warfront expecting attack by the LTTE rebels to mark their
victory at Kilinochchi where they defeated the government troops
and killed hundreds of them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
