<HEADLINE> Israel Welcomes Arab Ministers' Decision Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Israel has welcomed a
decision by Arab foreign ministers to avert the controversy over
the depiction of Jerusalem at the Israeli pavilion in Disney's
Epcot Park, Florida, U.S..
</P>
<P>
After holding a "special meeting" in New York on Friday with
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy, Arab foreign ministers
decided to accept reassurances from Disney that the Israeli
exhibit at the park will not refer to Jerusalem as the capital of
Israel, said the Israeli Foreign Ministry in a statement issued
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Levy's meeting with the Arab foreign ministers was held in an
amicable atmosphere following Levy's declaration that under no
circumstances would Israel accept the dual track of a political
campaign being conducted against Israel at the same time the peace
process moves ahead.
</P>
<P>
It was never Disney's intention to offer a political point of
view and Disney is an entertainment company dedicated to simply
bringing delight to its guests, said Disney executives.
</P>
<P>
But the Ministry's statement contradicted this clarification by
saying that anyone who visits the Israeli exhibit at Epcot will
receive a clear message that Jerusalem is Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
Some Arab states and organizations had threatened to boycott
Disney unless all references to Jerusalem being Israel's capital
at the Israeli pavilion were removed.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak has also asked the Disney not to
yield to Arab pressure regarding Israel's participation in the
Disney's millennium celebration.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts to harm Israel's standing on Jerusalem as its capital
failed in the past and would fail in the future," Barak said in
his statement last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
