<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Eyes Seven Golds in South Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh may win at least
seven golds and rank fourth in the medals tally at the eighth
South Asian Federation Games (SAF), The Star Sport reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The eighth SAF, the biggest sporting festival of the seven
South Asian countries, opened in the Nepalese capital Kathmandu on
Saturday and will last till October 4.
</P>
<P>
"The disciplines to which we are mostly looking forward is
shooting and with a little bit of luck, we might also win the
football gold," contingent general manger Lutful Huq was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He blamed "bad luck" for Bangladesh never winning the football
gold despite having reached the SAF final for a record five times.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that Bangladesh had good prospects in three events
of athletics -- men's 100m, men's 200m and men's 4x100m relay.
</P>
<P>
"We will win more medals in the games where mental toughness in
needed, and with a standard we have high hopes of winning a
considerable number of silver medals," he said.
</P>
<P>
He believes that India would win almost half of the 159 gold
medals, and Pakistan and Sri Lank might remain in the second and
third positions.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh might also win gold medals from swimming and
taekwondo, accordng to a report in The Independent daily newspaper,
quoting Shahabuddin Chaklader, member secretary of the Bangladesh
Olympic Association training and coaching committee.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh posted its best performance in Dhaka in the 6th SAF
Games 1993 when they clinched 11 golds.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi contingent consisting of 172 members, including
135 athletes (106 men and 29 women), will participate in all the
12 disciplines of the games -- athletics, boxing, football, karate,
kabaddi, shooting, swimming, table tennis, taekwondo, volleyball,
weightlifting and wrestling. 
