<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Sets to Work Against Honor Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 26 (Xinhua) -- A national anti-honor crimes
committee of Jordan has garnered 8,000 signatures in the first
month of a national campaign to cancel clauses in the penal code
to pardon or reduce the penalties for alleged honor killers.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the press on Sunday, the independent National
Jordanian Campaign Committee to Eliminate Crimes of Honor said it
had distributed 713 petition sheets among citizens in various
parts of the desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
In the petition, the group called on the government to abolish
Article 340 of the penal code, which pardons or reduce prison
terms for men who killed their wives or female relatives for
actual or suspected involvement in illicit relationships.
</P>
<P>
More than 25 women are killed each year in the kingdom with a
4.7 million population for honor-related reasons, according to
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The statement praised the efforts of hundreds of concerned
citizens who volunteered to help collect signatures and called on
everyone to joint the effort either by signing the petition or by
helping to gather more signatures.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was initiated by a group of Jordanians who claimed
they have no personal, political or racial interests, but to
"secure a good and safe life, free of violence in a society that
protects the rights of all."
</P>
<P>
In July this year, a special committee under the ministry of
justice decided to cancel Article 340 in the penal code, but the
decision still needs endorsement of the lower and upper house,
followed by a Royal Decree. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0126 </DOCNO>
