<HEADLINE> Organizers Name 2002 Winter Olympic Mascots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The organizers of the 2002
Winter Olympic Games announced the names of the mascots Saturday
in Salt Lake City, the United States.
</P>
<P>
A rabbit called Powder, a coyote named Copper and a bear named
Coal are the furry critters. The organizers hope to bring the kind
of money to the games that Utah's skiing, copper industry, coal
mining have brought the state.
</P>
<P>
It was expected that the mascots can generate at least $1
million. The stuffed animals will go on sale early as this holiday
season in Utah for $10 to $40.
</P>
<P>
The snowshoe hare, coyote and bear, all characters in western
Indian myth, first appeared in May. After the unveiling, SLOC
opened up the suggested names to a nationwide vote. The other
options were Sky, Cliff and Shadow or Arrow, Bolt and Rocky.
</P>
<P>
SLOC President Mitt Romney said the names represent Utah, with"
Powder" symbolizing the state's claim to "the greatest snow on
earth" and "Copper" and "Coal" representing the land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
