<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Sets Conditions for Funding Bangladesh Power Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) has set some pre-conditions for funding the proposed "Dhaka
Power System Upgrading Project" of the Dhaka Electric Supply
Authority (DESA), The Bangladesh Observer newspaper reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting official sources, the paper said the conditions include
separation of transmission and distribution systems from the Power
Development Board (PDB) to lessen the state monopoly on the
county's power sector.
</P>
<P>
The ADB agreed earlier to provide 150 million U.S. dollars to
the project to help improve power supply in the capital city,
Dhaka, and reduce system loss and pilferage in power distribution
in the DESA area.
</P>
<P>
ADB's resident representative in Dhaka Phipphit Suphaphiphat
said in a recent letter to the Bangladesh Energy Ministry that the
ADB would provide necessary fund to the "Dhaka Power System
Upgrading Project" only after getting the government's assurance
of fulfilling the conditions, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB asked the Energy Ministry to respond to the
pre-conditions by October 13 this year.
</P>
<P>
The ADB would hold official discussions on the project with the
government by the middle of next month, Suphaphiphat was quoted as
saying. "ADB's intention is to help the government to improve its
power sector. But it depends on the government's policy measures
to create a favorable situation for the fund providers," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the power sector should be "un-bundled" by transferring
the transmission and distribution systems to different
organizations other than the PDB and the DESA.
</P>
<P>
The Energy Ministry at a meeting in April this year admitted
that the DESA failed to supply around 300 megawatts of electricity
due to lack of proper transmission lines and observed that some
new transmission lines should be built on an emergency basis to
reduce loadshedding in the capital city, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The country's total electricity demand is about 2,300 megawatts
while the production capacity of the PDB is between 2,000 and
2,100 megawatts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
