<HEADLINE> Jordanian Opposition Rejects Peace Treaty With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Some 460 representatives from
13 Jordanian parties, 12 professional associations and labor
unions have reiterated rejection to the 1994 peace treaty between
Jordan and Israel.
</P>
<P>
In a 15-point resolution adopted after a second
anti-normalization conference concluded on Saturday, the
representatives called on Arabs to refrain from recognizing
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The resolution lauded armed resistance against Israeli
occupation in South Lebanon, and called for Arabs to support
the Lebanese in their struggle for freedom.
</P>
<P>
The resolution denounced Arab governments for their drive
against Palestinian resistance movements.
</P>
<P>
It called on the Jordanian government in particular to release
two senior leaders of the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) and
their associates arrested during a month-long crackdown on the
movement, and to "open a new page to enable the group to pursue
its struggle against the Zionist occupation."
</P>
<P>
Hamas politburo chief Khalid Mishaal and spokesman Ibrahim
Gosheh were still under detention with 19 of their associates on
charges of engaging in illegal political activities and holding
military exercises in Jordan as part of Hamas campaigns against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The anti-normalization conference, the second of its kind since
1995, represented a strong anti-Israel sentiment in the 4.7
million Jordanian population, of whom over 60 percent are of
Palestinian origins.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, and the
government has based its foreign policies on keeping friendly
relations with all neighbor countries, including Israel.
</P>
<P>
The desert kingdom has also been a firm supporter and broker of
the peace process between Israel and its Arab neighbors, including
the Palestinians, Lebanon and Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
