<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-7 Promises to Promote Global Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Major industrial nations
pledged Saturday to make further joint efforts to improve the
international economic outlook and to strengthen financial
stability.
</P>
<P>
The finance ministers and central bank governors of the Group
of Seven (G-7) industrialized countries, who held a one-day
meeting here, agreed that the global economic outlook has improved.
</P>
<P>
The improved outlook has been characterized by the beginnings
of a foundation for balanced and widely shared growth in the major
industrial countries, and a solidifying recovery in emerging
markets in Asia, G-7 said in a statement issued after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
In the United States and Canada, prospects are favorable for
another year of solid growth and job creation in a low-inflation
environment, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministers and governors agreed that the world is
still faced with a number of challenges in fostering a strong and
sustained world recovery with financial stability.
</P>
<P>
"In our discussions of the global economy, we recognized that
it is important not to take recent improvements in the global
outlook for granted and that there remain serious challenges ahead,
" said U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers at a press
conference after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
G-7 members are Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, the
United Kingdom and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, while reaffirming the importance of progress in
achieving a more balanced pattern of growth among the G-7
economies, urged the emerging market economies to continue to
focus on reform to promote the basis for lasting growth.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for Japan's economy, the second largest economy in
the world, and the impact of the rising yen on its fledgling
recovery figured high on the agenda of the G-7.
</P>
<P>
On exchange rates, the statement said: "We shared Japan's
concern about the potential impact of the yen's appreciation for
the Japanese economy and the world economy."
</P>
<P>
"We welcomed indications by the Japanese authorities that
policies would be conducted appropriately in view of this
potential impact," said the statement. "We will continue to
monitor developments in exchange markets and cooperate as
appropriate."
</P>
<P>
Japanese authorities pledged to "implement stimulus measures
until domestic-demand- led growth is solidly in place and, in the
context of their zero interest rate policy, to provide ample
liquidity until deflationary concerns are dispelled." the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also discussed debt reduction and poverty reduction,
strengthening the international financial and monetary system,
anti-corruption and the Russian economy, the U.S. secretary of
treasury said.
</P>
<P>
The seven countries urged the Russian authorities to step up
economic reforms and combat the critical problems of corruption
and money laundering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Recovery Still Fragile in Developing World: G-24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Group of 24 (G-24)
developing countries said here Saturday that global economic
prospects and financial markets have improved in the last few
months, but the recovery in the developing world remains quite
fragile.
</P>
<P>
"A number of risks and uncertainties continue to pose
challenges for policymakers," G-24 said in a communique issued
after a one-day meeting of their ministers.
</P>
<P>
A major concern arises from the unbalanced growth pattern among
major industrial countries, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
Despite some stabilization in international financial markets,
net capital flows to developing countries and transition economies
have not yet recovered from the very low level in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the distribution of flows remains uneven, and
interest rate spreads are still very large, the communique said.
Oil prices remain volatile, non-fuel commodity prices remain
depressed, and an early improvement appears unlikely in developing
countries' terms of trade.
</P>
<P>
Despite the various initiatives currently in place to address
the problems of the heavily indebted poor countries, comprehensive
relief is yet to be achieved, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 countries called on wealthy nations to provide "
broader, deeper and faster debt relief for heavily indebted
countries to help fight poverty," said Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga, current chairman of the G-24.
</P>
<P>
The ministers considered that the uncertainty surrounding the
sustainability of global growth requires a parallel effort on the
part of industrial countries, particularly by strengthening
macroeconomic policy coordination.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 countries called for greater involvement of private
investors and creditors in overcoming their countries' financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The major challenge for the international community is to
develop a market-friendly strategy for involving the private
sector in a manner that does not disrupt or unduly raise the cost
of capital flows to developing countries," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
The G-24, which represents the developing world at the annual
meetings of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World
Bank, will present their views to the IMF policy-making Interim
Committee meeting here Sunday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
