<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Foreign Exchange Reserve Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's foreign currency
reserve has been declining, from a record 3 billion U.S. dollars
in 1994 to the present 1.5 billion dollars which is the lowest in
about half a decade's time, the newspaper The New Nation reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The low foreign currency reserve figured prominently in a
recent meeting here between representatives of donor countries
and Bangladesh government officials. Donors in the meeting
expressed their acute worry over the declining reserve and
stressed all-out efforts to raise it.
</P>
<P>
Many donor countries have considerable investments in
Bangladesh. Therefore, they have a stake in uninterrupted debt
servicing and repatriation of their investments and profits.
</P>
<P>
Experts in the country noted that a good or satisfactory
reserve situation is the best guarantee of the continuous inflow
of foreign direct investments (FDIs). FDIs are much sought after
in Bangladesh against the backdrop of its low internal rate of
investments, they said. They added that FDIs are the main hope of
investments which can cater to the desperate needs of employment
and earnings in the country.
</P>
<P>
The experts expressed their concerns about the situation of the
foreign exchange reserve of the country in a report published here
on Sunday. A significant boost in export and increase in foreign
currency remittances can notably increase the reserve in a short
period of time, the report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, better governmental policy planning
and execution would be necessary to substantially increase
earnings from these two sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Prime Minister Leaves for New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister
Krishna Prasad Bhattarai left here for New York Sunday morning as
head of the Nepalese delegation to the 54th U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Bhattarai is scheduled to address the U.N. General Assembly on
September 30.
</P>
<P>
During the session, the Nepalese delegation will stress the
need for additional measures and resources from the international
community for Nepal's political and social development.
</P>
<P>
Nepal will also call on the international community to work for
disarmament, especially elimination of nuclear weapons in a
time-bound manner and will address issues related to peacekeeping
and reforms of the United Nations.
</P>
