<HEADLINE> Venezuela Denies Intervention in Colombia's Internal Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Venezuelan government
Saturday refuted Colombia's charges that Venezuela has intervened
in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
In a communique, Venezuelan Foreign Minister Jose Vicente
Rangel said that the Venezuelan government does not understand the
statement made by Colombian President Andres Pastrana in a recent
interview with Washington Post, which asked Venezuelan President
Hugo Chavez to keep away from Colombia's problems.
</P>
<P>
Rangel emphasized that the Chavez government, aware of what is
going on in its neighboring country, has adopted a prudent stand
based on non-intervention and has at the same time shown its
willingness to contribute to the solution of the Colombian crisis.
</P>
<P>
President Pastrana was quoted by the press as saying, "What I
am asking of Chavez is to keep himself in his own terrain, and
that we will manage our own problems."
</P>
<P>
Colombia has been in a civil war for decades, during which
leftist guerrillas, rightist paramilitary organizations and
government forces fought for control of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan foreign minister complained that his country
suffered a lot from the fallout of Colombia's internal troubles,
citing repeated intrusion across the border, hijackings,
kidnapping and killing of Venezuelan citizens, as well as the
refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
Rangel denied that the Venezuelan government had any part in
Colombia's internal crisis.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the ongoing peace talks in Venezuela between Colombia
's civil society representatives and the National Liberation Army
(ELN), he stressed that his country had been requested to be the
host and that it has the permission of the Colombian government,
as was the case for similar meetings held in Venezuela before.
</P>
</TEXT>
