<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-7 Vows to Strengthen Global Financial Architecture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Major industrial nations
vowed here Saturday to build a stronger global financial system,
based on more robust national policies to avoid crisis, as well as
a better international capacity to respond when crisis occurs.
</P>
<P>
Finance ministers and central bank governors from the Group of
Seven (G-7) industrialized countries met and reviewed the progress
towards strengthening the international financial architecture.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 ministers have launched a new G-20 mechanism for dialog
among key industrial and emerging market economies, with the first
meeting expected in December.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 countries are Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan,
the United Kingdom and the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers, they
"shared a collective sense of impatience" to do all they can in
the coming year to implement further concrete steps in this regard.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to reduce national vulnerability to crisis with
better management of their external balance sheets to avoid a
buildup of unstable debt, and with efforts to promote sustainable
exchange rate regimes in emerging market economies.
</P>
<P>
The ministers decided to press further with coordination
between the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank
in the crucial areas relating to financial stability and
successful development, with shared work and emphasis on
strengthening the critical infrastructure for countries' financial
systems, ranging from banking supervision, corporate governance,
and bankruptcy regimes to the social agenda.
</P>
<P>
On the crucial issue of crisis resolution, the ministers
reaffirmed the framework of principles and tools that they
endorsed in their Report to Heads in June, noting the need to
maintain flexibility to address diverse cases effectively.
</P>
<P>
"We stressed the importance of supporting a stable flow of
capital to emerging markets, that reflected market judgments of
countries' economic and financial prospects," Summers said at a
press conference after the G-7 meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
