<HEADLINE> Time Limit to be Set for Re-employment Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Re-employment services
centers (RSCs) set up to help China's laid-off workers from State-
owned enterprises (SOEs) are likely to consigned to history by
2003, today's China Daily (Business Weekly) reported.
</P>
<P>
An improved social insurance network, including unemployment
insurance, old-age pensions and medicare insurance, will take over
the RSC's responsibilities and be used to protect the unemployment,
Beijing Mayor Liu Qi said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is one of the first cities to try out the practice.
</P>
<P>
For decades, China pursued full employment at expense of
economic efficiency. With workers unused to the sudden SOE reforms
in mid-1990s, RSCs were established to come to help those layoffs.
</P>
<P>
RSCs take in laid-off workers from SOEs and offer to help them
find new jobs. The centers also give financial subsidies above the
normal level of unemployment insurance.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the subsidies is shared equally by the SOEs that
have laid off the workers, the local government and the RSCs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
