<HEADLINE> Myanmar FM on Globalization Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has warned that the
process of globalization, which can facilitate economic
development and enhance the living standards of people, can also
make smaller and less developed states vulnerable to undesirable
negative effects.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the general debate of the 54th session of the U.N.
General Assembly in New York Friday, Myanmar Foreign Minister U
Win Aung pointed out that one such problem, caused by the process
of globalization, is transnational crime which includes illicit
trafficking of narcotic drugs, money laundering, trafficking in
persons, arms smuggling, piracy and terrorism, official newspaper
The New Light of Myanmar reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that these crimes pose serious threats to the
peace and stability of mankind at both national and regional
levels.
</P>
<P>
He called for national, regional and global response to deal
with the nature of the problem.
</P>
<P>
He cited Myanmar's hosting of the Second Ministerial Meeting of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations on transnational crime
in June this year as a bid to strengthen cooperation in the
regional grouping to cope with the problem.
</P>
<P>
The successful hosting of the meeting constituted a significant
step in advancing the regional cooperation in combating the menace
in Southeast Asia, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Myanmar has adopted a master plan to totally
eradicate poppy cultivation in the country within 15 years, saying
the Mongla region in Shan state has been declared an "opium-free
zone" with law enforcement stepped up in the border areas,
resulting in increased seizure of narcotic drugs. 
</P>
