<HEADLINE> China's First Asset Management Co. Outlines Debt Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- China first asset management
corporation, Cinda, has said it will go beyond debt-equity swaps
to help pull State-owned enterprises (SOEs) out of their
difficulties, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The State has pinned high hopes on debt-equity swaps to rescue
troubled SOEs. The Fourth Plenary Session of the 15th Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), which concluded
on Wednesday, reiterated the utmost importance of meeting a three-
year (1998-2000) turn-around target for these firms.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xiaozhou is executive director of the investment banking
department of Cinda, China's first professional handler of non-
performing loans. He pledged that the company would focus on
follow-up measures to help restructure and streamline SOEs in
which it will hold shares.
</P>
<P>
The crux of the operation is to initiate restructuring and
streamlining drives within the enterprises, Chen said, adding that
this could be facilitated by the alleviation of their financial
burden by debt-equity swaps.
</P>
<P>
The operations of new companies will strictly follow the
guidelines worked out by its board of directors. Creditors' rights,
which used to be vague in SOEs, will be clarified to ensure the
firm's healthy development, Chen added.  
</P>
