<HEADLINE> Brazil to Expand Rocket Launching Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian Airport
Infrastructure Company (Infraero) is planning to invest 26.3
million U.S. dollars in expanding the country's Alcantara
Launching Center (CLA).
</P>
<P>
The plan aims to transform the center into a pole of attraction
for the Brazilian space industry and to place the country in the
world market of satellite launching, said Joao Ribeiro Junior,
head of Infraero's Aerospace Development Department, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The company is expected to build in the next 10 years three or
four launch pads for medium and large rockets.
</P>
<P>
An agreement signed by the Aeronautics Ministry and the Space
Agency will guarantee Infraero for 15 years of responsibility for
the CLA's commercial development, implementation of logistics
infrastructures, and construction and operation of new launching
sites.
</P>
<P>
The CLA, located in the northern Maranhao state and created
solely for military strategies in the 1980s as part of the
Brazilian Space Program, started commercial activities in 1989.
</P>
<P>
A total of 256 meteorological and sounding satellites have been
launched from the center so far. 
</P>
