<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for More Active Participation in Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- China urged developing
countries to take a more active stance toward participating in
globalization to achieve and maintain a steady development as the
Group of 24 developing countries held a ministerial meeting here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting, Chinese Vice Minister of Finance Jin
Liqun said that globalization, for the benefit of all members of
the international community, must rule out the zero-sum game under
the law of the jungle and embrace a mechanism for a win-win
solution on the basis of equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
He said that in reforming the international financial structure,
full participation by developing countries is required, and their
views should be fully respected.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the international financial architecture to be
worked out must be multi-dimensional. It should not just cover
international standards and codes of conduct in macro policy and
structural reforms," he said.
</P>
<P>
The thrust of the reforms is to solve the substantive issues of
the international financial structure, such as on international
monetary system and management of international capital flow, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries should have their opportunities to
participate fully in the discussions for this purpose, he noted.
</P>
<P>
G-24 was formed at the 1972 Lima meeting of the Group of 77 to
represent the interests of the developing countries in
negotiations on international monetary matters.
</P>
<P>
On trade liberalization, Jin said, "We have to concern
ourselves with the fair share of benefits to the developing
countries and the balance of their rights against obligations in
the international trade system and the opportunities expected of
trade liberalization."
</P>
<P>
Jin urged the international community to push the
implementation of the agreements concluded in Uruguay Round in a "
concrete effective and balanced way," particularly those areas
related to the interests of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"The forthcoming new round of multilateral trade negotiations
should take into full account developing countries' concerns and
needs, and work towards a more open and fair multilateral trade
system, thereby contributing to the balanced development of the
world economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jin called on developed countries and multilateral development
institutions to continue to support economic growth in under-
developed countries by providing resource transfers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
