<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Tibetans Marching on Socialist Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- New comers to Tibet often find
that the exotic land far exceeds their expectations, and those who
make return visits continue to marvel at the stunning changes,
Tibet's top government official said in a recent interview with
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Legqog, chairman of the Tibet Autonomous Regional People's
Government, comes from a long line of ethnic Tibetans. He swells
with pride when he talks about the progress Tibet has made since
1951 when it was peacefully liberated, especially since 1959 when
Tibet launched its democratic reform which helped the people out
of serfdom and into socialism.
</P>
<P>
"Since the democratic reform, Tibetans have become masters of
their own destiny," he said, adding that "Currently, they are
marching towards a well-off life, and a united, prosperous and
civilized socialist, new Tibet has emerged."
</P>
<P>
Legqog called the great changes that have occurred in Tibet,
which covers 1.2 million square kilometers, a "miracle in the
world."
</P>
<P>
Over the past decades, Tibet has achieved a sustainable, fast
and healthy development. In 1998, its gross domestic product
reached 9.12 billion yuan, 48.1 times the 1959 figure. Since 1994,
Tibet has been developing at double-digit rate annually, faster
than the national average.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the average annual per-capita income in Tibet
surpassed 5,400 yuan for urbanites and 1,158 yuan for rural
residents, 5.31 times and 7.7 times of the 1959 figures,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
To date, the number of poor Tibetans has been decreased to 110,
000, as 90 percent of the Tibetan people have adequate food and
clothing.
</P>
<P>
Legqog attributed the enormous changes to the support of the
central government and the aid of Chinese people in other parts of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Since 1959, the central government has allocated over 40
billion yuan for building infrastructure in Tibet, while other
parts of the country have also helped this ethnic autonomous
region build 105 key projects, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
During his interview with Xinhua, Legqog reiterated that the
fast economic progress in Tibet has consistently improved the
living standards of the Tibetan people and enabled them to enjoy
their full rights of existence and development.
</P>
<P>
According to the chairman, since Tibet was made an autonomous
region, it has established the regional law-making body, the
people's congress, and deputies to people's congresses at all
levels have fully exercised their rights to represent the
interests of Tibetan people. So far, Tibet has issued more than
150 local laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
According to Legqog, Tibetan officials now account for 74.9
percent of the total in Tibet, while 63 percent of professionals
of all kinds are ethnic Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
These days, the Tibetan people are enjoying wide-ranging and
comprehensive rights in political, economic, cultural and
educational fields, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
