<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar FM on U.N. Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar said it is encouraged
to see that the U.N. General Assembly has adopted a resolution on
the requirement of a two-thirds majority in taking decisions and
resolutions on the question of reform of the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
In a statement in the general debate of the 54th session of the
U.N. General Assembly in New York Friday, Myanmar Foreign Minister
U Win Aung said that as a member of the Non-Alignment Movement,
Myanmar's preference for the enlargement of the Security Council
is up to 26, the official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar favors the expansion of the council membership in both
categories, permanent and non-permanent, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In order to overcome the current impasse on the question of
permanent seats in the Security Council, a compromise formula,
acceptable to all parties, should be worked out through enhanced
consultations and discussions among the member states," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is of the view that in the event of other options
having failed to command enough support, the idea of rotating
permanent seats should also be considered as one of the options in
the permanent membership category, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
