<HEADLINE> Colombian Government, Leftist Guerrilla to Resume Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian
government and the leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia
(FARC) have agreed to resume peace talks within 10 days, said
reports reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after two days of talks between the
FARC and senior government delegate Victor G. Ricardo, said
guerrilla spokesman Luis Eduardo Devia in San Vicente del Caguan
in the demilitarized areas.
</P>
<P>
The talks will reopen without the participation of an
international verification commission, as the FARC opposes foreign
presence, Devia told Radio Caracol network.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between the government and the FARC, the biggest
guerrilla group in Colombia, started in January and halted in mid-
July because of the latter's objection to the international
verification commission.
</P>
<P>
According to Devia, FARC representatives and Ricardo will meet
again within the next few days to fix the schedule for the
upcoming talks, which, he disclosed, will be held in La Uribe, one
of the five demilitarized zones created by the Colombian
government last November in order to facilitate peace talks with
the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Colombia's demilitarized areas total 42,000 square kilometers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
