<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Benefiting From Urbanization (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- It used to be only a dream
for farmers in some parts of China of living as good a life as
urbanites did, enjoying modern-day life in an apartment with
electric house appliances.
</P>
<P>
But now the dream has come true for Wu Renbao, 72, in the
village of Huaxi in Jiangsu Province, east China, where he is the
Village Communist Party Committee secretary, after nearly 30 years
of struggle, strife, and untold suffering. In his younger years he
was a herdsman, but 1949, the year when New China was born, made
it possible for him to change his life and even help poverty-
stricken farmers in Huaxi.
</P>
<P>
In 1965, as a Party member, he planned to mobilize his fellow
villagers to bring a new look to Huaxi and worked with them to get
out of poverty and build tile-roofed brick houses and irrigation
ditches, develop farmland, and apply scientific farming methods.
</P>
<P>
Wu led the village in diversifying production into sideline and
industrial sectors, setting up more than 40 enterprises in the
village, with 95 percent of the labor force in the industrial and
service sectors.
</P>
<P>
In 1980, Huaxi ranked first in the province's villages, with
its 100 million yuan worth of industrial and agricultural output.
value
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
