<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Benefiting From Urbanization (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wu also gave much thought to the needs of the younger
generation and proposed building a park in the village in the
early 1980s, which, he thinks, is a good place for youngsters to
make friends.
</P>
<P>
Even more surprising, he had a roofed corridor built in the
village, running 10 kilometers from north to south to link the
village's houses, market, shop, hotel, park, and factories.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, he rented a plane for the more than 30 of the elderly
villagers up for a look at the development around Huaxi. They were
overwhelmed by the results and excited about their village. Aiming
even higher, Wu made it possible for Huaxi villagers to purchase
50 Volkswagens and Jettas in 1993, giving the farmers their own
cars for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Wu has reached most of his goals, but the old man is still
thinking about other things like the environment and education and
what else he can do for the village next century. Huaxi has become
known as the No. 1 village in China.
</P>
<P>
There are more cars here for every 100 people than that in
Singapore, so, in some people's eyes, Huaxi has created an
economic miracle similar to that of Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
