<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Advances into Davis Cup Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Former champions France reached
the Davis Cup final on Saturday with an unassailable 3-0 lead as
Fabrice Santoro and Olivier Delaitre scored an easy doubles
victory over Belgian pair Xavier Malisse and Christophe Van Garsse
in Pau.
</P>
<P>
France's opponents in the December 3-5 final will be either
Australia or Russia, who were battling out the other semi-final in
Brisbane where Australia were leading 2-1.
</P>
<P>
In the world group qualifiers, reigning champions Sweden
recovered from the shock of losing both singles matches to Austria,
hauling themselves back into the tie with a doubles win.
</P>
<P>
Spain, semifinalists for the last two years, became the first
nation to be sure of one of the eight world group qualifying
berths when they took a 3-0 lead over New Zealand in Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
The Czech Republic will also stay in the world group next year
after going 3-0 up against newcomers Uzbekistan in Tashkent.
</P>
<P>
France have had home advantage throughout this year's cup, and
the good luck will stay with them for the final as they will have
choice of ground whoever wins in Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
It will be the third final of the decade for the French, who
won the cup in 1991 and 1996 under Yannick Noah, and six times
between 1927 and 1932.
</P>
<P>
Santoro and Delaitre, ranked ninth in the world as a doubles
pair, beat Malisse and Van Garsse 6-3, 6-3, 6-3 after singles wins
by Cedric Pioline and Sebastien Grosjean on Friday.
</P>
<P>
In Brisbane, Australian Open champion Kafelnikov and partner
Andrei Olhovskiy beat the better fancied Australian duo of Sandon
Stolle and Mark Woodforde 6-1, 6-4, 4-6, 4-6, 8-6.
</P>
<P>
Three-times champions Germany go into the final day 2-1 up
against Romania after David Prinosil and Marc Kevin Goellner beat
Andrei Pavel and Gabriel Trifu 6-4, 6-0, 6-3 in the doubles.
</P>
<P>
Britain have worries about the fitness of world number six Greg
Rusedski who decided against playing doubles on Saturday, then
watched compatriots Tim Henman and Neil Broad lose in straight
sets to South Africa's David Adams and John-Laffnie de Jager.
</P>
<P>
With Britain 2-1 up in Birmingham, Rusedski plays the second
singles on Sunday, against Grant Stafford, after Henman meets
Neville Godwin.
</P>
<P>
Last year's finalists Italy were trailing Finland 2-1 in
Sardinia after a surprise doubles win by Ville Liukko and Tuomas
Ketola over Andrea Gaudenzi and Diego Nargiso. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
