<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Map Of Beijing Now Having To Be Updated Frequently </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Map of Beijing now has to be
updated once every month or even every week because of fast
changes now taking place here in the Chinese capital, according to
Li Zongshun, who has been working on cartography for more than
three decades.
</P>
<P>
Some people in Beijing say that they hardly recognize their
city any more even though they've lived here for years. Li said
that they used to only print city maps once a year, 500,000 at a
time, but now they only print 50,000 to 100,000 each time because
of the rapid urban growth.
</P>
<P>
A detailed map of Beijing that was printed in 1950 is the
oldest map at the China Map Publishing House. It has no price or
traffic lanes printed on it. The capital at that time was divided
into two parts -- an interior and an exterior.
</P>
<P>
Now, anyone can get a city map anywhere for just 3 yuan (about
0.36 U.S. cents). It shows four ring roads circling the city and
the urban area has grown from 62 sq. km.to over 400 sq. km.
</P>
<P>
The publishing house spent about 31 million yuan (about 3.72
million U.S. dollars) improving production by buying computers in
1994 to keep up with changes in the city.
</P>
<P>
October 1, this year, is the 50th anniversary of the founding
of New China and 67 key projects are being finished for the
occasion, so the publishing house is preparing the most recent map.
</P>
<P>
It's less than one week since the last map was printed,
according to Wang Jixian, head of the publishing house.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
