<DOCNO> XIE19990926.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahuad Seeks To Reduce Foreign Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Ecuadoran President Jamil
Mahuad Saturday asked the international financing organizations to
reduce the burden of the Ecuadoran foreign debt because of the
economic incapacity of the country.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador cannot pay the present debt of 16 billion U.S. dollars,
said Mahuad in his Saturday speech broadcast to all the nation.
</P>
<P>
The Ecuadoran debt is in proportion the highest of Latin
America, and the government searches for a reduction of the debt
burden in the budget, the economy and the exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have (in Ecuador) a very special situation, that must be
considered here and abroad," said the president.
</P>
<P>
He said that an Ecuadoran mission headed by Central Bank
President Pablo Better traveled some days ago to Washington to
meet with International Monetary Fund, World Bank and U.S.
Treasury officials.
</P>
<P>
The Ecuadoran government wants to renegotiate in the next days
96 million dollars in interests due next Tuesday for its Brady
bonds debt of almost 6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The president said that if the Ecuadoran foreign debt keeps at
the present levels, "it does not have an exit in the future."
</P>
<P>
Ecuador is facing its worst economic slum. The South American
country is technically in default of it 5.9 billion dollars in
Brandy bonds. Its total debt burden of 16 billion dollars is
representing 110 percent of the country's gross domestic product.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
